Final Project

Kelly Cook

First Responders Mental Health Awareness Survey

Survey Data Analysis

Background

This survey is considered a “First Responders Mental Health Awareness Survey” or a Wellness and Support Questionnaire. It’s designed to give the administration a picture of how their department is doing based on their members’ self-reporting. The survey is broken up into sections measuring different areas of life first responders are typically most affected in.

Cleaning the data

Cleaning the raw data was an extencive work. This particular data sets department membership has 545 sworn officers, 119 civilian members (non-officers). 324 responded (but not to every question)-approximately 48.80% response rate.There is an .Rproj in this folder that contains the primary cleaning. The data will be divided in five color coded sections for convinience.

Data overview

df <- read.csv("./Police_clean.cvs")
skim(df)
glimpse(df)
df <- na.omit(df)
df$Position <- factor(df$Position) 
levels(df$Position) <- c("Sworn", "Disp")
df$how.many.years <- factor(df$how.many.years)
levels(df$how.many.years) <- c("1-6", "7-13", "14-20", "20+")

The survey was administered to Sworn Officer and Law Enforcement Professional (Dispatch or other Civilian Department Member). Which if found in the data as Position = “Sworn” and “Disp”

Figure 2b. Correlation grph. EPA Qiestions

Step4

Finding the best model

mod1 <- lm(formula = likeE ~ whatE, data = dat)
mod2 <- lm(formula = likeE ~ howE, data = dat)
summary(mod2)#whatE is a better predictor to likeE
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = likeE ~ howE, data = dat)
## 
## Residuals:
##     Min      1Q  Median      3Q     Max 
## -1.7074 -0.7075  0.2925  0.7526  2.2925 
## 
## Coefficients:
##             Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept)   3.1675     0.1556  20.354  < 2e-16 ***
## howE         -0.4600     0.1095  -4.203 3.54e-05 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 0.8756 on 283 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.05874,    Adjusted R-squared:  0.05542 
## F-statistic: 17.66 on 1 and 283 DF,  p-value: 3.542e-05
mod1mse <- mean(residuals(mod1)^2)
mod2mse <- mean(residuals(mod2)^2)
su2<- summary((mod2))$r.squared
su1<- summary((mod1))$r.squared
mod1mse ; mod2mse ; su1 ; su2
## [1] 0.725485
## [1] 0.7613033
## [1] 0.1030272
## [1] 0.05874243

whatE seems to be a beeter predictore for likeE. However, it explains only 10% of the varience.

Step5

Graphing models + predicctions

effect_plot(mod1, pred = whatE, plot.points = TRUE, jitter = 0)

Figure 2c.Likely to usu EPA with respect What is EPA**
